hat notion has now taken on a new quality in architectural discourse. Today when we speak of simulation we primarily think of "computer simulation," the technical ability to simulate processes. Whereas simulation used to refer to a mode of presentation, it now connects architecture with the sciences and represents a strategic and methodological instrument, a tool of discovery. With the scientific principle of simulation the focus shifts to the idea of "modeling a dynamic system" (Norbert Wiener), not just presenting finished products but going in search of solutions and developing systems!  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchitecturexSimulation methods. 4aArchitectural theory. 4aArt. 4aCAAD. 4aCultural studies. 4aDesign. 4aMedia sciences. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh1 aGleiniger, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleiniger, Andrea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGleiniger, Andrea.1 aGramelsberger, Gabriele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGramelsberger, Gabriele.1 aHänsli, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHänsli, Thomas.1 aHörl, Erich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHörl, Erich.1 aRöller, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRöller, Nils.1 aVrachliotis, Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVrachliotis, Georg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVrachliotis, Georg.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Architecture, Design and Arts 2000 - 2014z9783110635690oZDB-23-GAA08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Art and Architecture 2000-2014 (EN)z9783110621